                                                                                                                           6                                                                                      NTPC in Bangla deal
          OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT                          Power pact                                  
	New Delhi, Aug 30: State-run power producer NTPC today entered into a preliminary agreement with the Bangladesh Power Development Board for two thermal power plants in Chittagong and Khulna to meet power shortage in Dhaka.        
	An MoU has been signed today between NTPC and the Bangladesh Power Development Board (BPDB) for setting up two 1,320MW each power projects at Chittagong and Khulna in Bangladesh, an official statement said.        
	NTPC and the BPDB are likely to hold 50 per cent each in the projects and invest around Rs 13,200 crore.        
	The Indian PSU will run the project and use imported coal.        
	Power secretary P. Uma Shankar said the parties expected to complete feasibility studies by January.        
	According to the World Bank, power shortage in Bangladesh is about 2,000MW during peak hours.        
	NTPC is likely to pick up a stake in two coal mines in Indonesia to meet its burgeoning energy requirements. The companys coal requirement is likely to touch 165 million tonnes (mt) in the next financial year (2011-12), of which it may import 12-15mt.        
	We are looking at picking up a stake in two coal mines in Indonesia  East Kalimanthan and Sumatra, chairman-cum-managing director R. S. Sharma said.        
	NTPC is also in talks with merchant bankers for acquiring 2-3 coal blocks in the Australian states of Queensland and New South Wales.        
	Sharma said the company had offered a stake in its 350MW gas-based Kayamkulam plant in Kerala to Qatar Petroleum.                                                                                                                                       
